# DFL Asset Loading

All asset loading goes through the framework's `AssetRef` system and `IContainerBuilder` methods. Direct Unity API calls are prohibited in game code.

## Prohibited Patterns

```csharp
// BAD -- hardcoded string, synchronous, no caching, no lifecycle
var asset = Resources.Load<MyAsset>("path/to/asset");

// BAD -- bypasses framework download/retry/lifecycle management
var handle = Addressables.LoadSceneAsync(sceneRef, LoadSceneMode.Additive);

// BAD -- wrong type; use framework SceneAssetRef instead
[SerializeField] private AssetReference _sceneRef;
```

## Correct Pattern

Declare a typed `AssetRef` field on a `ContainerBuilderFactory` ScriptableObject, then register it on the builder. The framework handles async loading, caching, download (for Addressables), and cleanup on container disposal.

```csharp
public sealed class LevelContainerFactory : ContainerBuilderFactory
{
    [SerializeField] private ScriptableObjectAssetRefT<InputActionAsset> _inputActions = default!;
    [SerializeField] private GameplayContainerFactory _gameplayFactory = default!;

    public override IContainerBuilder AddToBuilder(IContainerBuilder builder)
    {
        return builder
            .AddScriptableObject(_inputActions)  // loaded async, injected via [Dependency]
            .AddSingleton(_gameplayFactory)
            .AddTransient<IRunnable, LevelState>();
    }
}
```

The resolved asset is then injected into the consuming class:

```csharp
public sealed class InputService : IInputService, IInitializable
{
    [Dependency] private readonly InputActionAsset _actions = default!;  // injected by container

    public UniTask Initialize(CancellationToken token)
    {
        // _actions is already loaded -- just use it
        InputActionMap map = _actions.FindActionMap("Player", throwIfNotFound: true)!;
        // ...
    }
}
```

## Scene Loading

Use `AddScene(SceneAssetRef)` on the builder. The scene loads during `Build()` and auto-unloads when the container disposes:

```csharp
// GOOD
await using (IContainer level = await _container
    .CreateChild("Level")
    .AddFromBuilder(_levelFactory)
    .AddScene(levelDefinition.SceneRef)  // SceneAssetRef, not AssetReference
    .Build(token))
{
    await level.Run<IRunnable>(token);
}
// scene auto-unloads here

// BAD
var handle = Addressables.LoadSceneAsync(level.SceneRef, LoadSceneMode.Additive);
// ... manual unload later
await Addressables.UnloadSceneAsync(sceneInstance);
```

## Scene MonoBehaviour Injection

Use the generic `AddScene<T>()` overloads to register MonoBehaviours from a loaded scene as injectable dependencies. The framework scans the scene's root objects for the specified type and throws `GameException` if not found. This replaces `FindAnyObjectByType` / `FindObjectOfType`.

```csharp
// GOOD -- register scene MonoBehaviours through the container
public override IContainerBuilder AddToBuilder(IContainerBuilder builder)
{
    return builder
        .AddScene<PixelPipelineController>(_sceneRef)   // single type
        .AddScene<PlayerSpawn, EnemySpawn>(_sceneRef)    // two types from same scene
        .AddTransient<IRunnable, LevelState>();
}

// Then inject via [Dependency] -- guaranteed non-null or Build() throws
public sealed class PixelPipelineService : IPixelPipelineService
{
    [Dependency] private readonly PixelPipelineController _controller = default!;

    public void SetWorldZoom(float zoom) => _controller.WorldZoom = zoom;
}

// BAD -- bypasses DI, null result is silent, requires null guards everywhere
controller = Object.FindAnyObjectByType<PixelPipelineController>();
if (controller == null) Debug.LogWarning("Not found");
```

When a scene is loaded via `AddScene(SceneAssetRef)`, the `AddScene<T>` overload reuses that same scene reference. The `Find<T>` resolver waits for the scene to finish loading, then scans root GameObjects. If the MonoBehaviour is not found, `Build()` fails with a `GameException` -- making missing scene objects a build-time error, not a silent runtime null.

## Available AssetRef Types

| Type | Builder method | Injects as |
|------|---------------|------------|
| `SceneAssetRef` | `AddScene(ref)` | `Scene` |
| `ScriptableObjectAssetRefT<T>` | `AddScriptableObject(ref)` | `T` |
| `AudioClipAssetRef` | `AddAudioClip(ref)` | `AudioClip` |
| `GameObjectAssetRef` | `AddGameObjectManager(ref, options)` | `IGameObjectManager` |
| `GameObjectAssetRefT<T>` | `AddGameObjectManager(ref, options)` | `IGameObjectManagerT<T>` |
| `SpriteAssetRef` | `AddSprite(ref)` | `Sprite` |
| `Texture2DAssetRef` | `AddTextures2D(ref)` | `Texture2D` |
| `MeshAssetRef` | `AddMesh(ref)` | `Mesh` |
| `SpriteAtlasAssetRef` | `AddSpriteAtlas(ref)` | `SpriteAtlas` |
| `AtlasedSpriteAssetRef` | `AddAtlasedSprite(ref)` | `Sprite` |

Each `AssetRef` supports both `Resources` and `Addressables` mode via the `AssetRefMode` enum. The mode is configured per-asset in the Inspector; the code does not change between modes.

## The Only Exception

`Main.cs` in the framework loads `MainArgs` via `Resources.Load("MainArgs")`. This is framework bootstrap code. Game code must NEVER call `Resources.Load` directly.
